that often I don’t get the feeling that my the special editors truly care about ‘me’, the non fictional character of sorts. It really does feel like you’re just a mere piece of meat, a dollar sign that COULD become a regular source of income for them. Let’s not get me wrong, they genuinely try. But mostly none of them is dedicated enough to go the extra mile, often assuming its the “responsibility of the parent” to figure certain issues out. — Finally! A rule kick starting the end of bullying in Irish schools is about to come to an end, in other words, about to be abolished. Parents can submit a bullying complaint to the schools but the onus seems to be mainly with the parent. In my opinion if this rule is abuslelly thrown out then it is badly implemented and never will work. >>> In other words, nothing will change. Again, if the root cause of bullying is rooted out in the very first place it will not become a problem as the victim will not be vulnerable and so will not be targeted.

Tweedale: It’s difficult to accept that’s the case in our country - but your wisdom is telling you what surely must (by now) be obvious-Ireland waste a great deal of time – optimistically hoping their dealings with the English-speaking world will, eventually, move in their favour.
